<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Chapter 6: The Contrapositive</title>
  <p>A conditional statement is logically equivalent to its <term>contrapositive</term>. That is,
<md>(P\implies Q) \leftrightarrow (\sim Q \implies \sim P).</md></p>
  <p>We proved this using truth tables on page 66 of class worksheets and in the preview activity for today. This also makes intuitive sense, considering the examples on pages 5 and 65 of class worksheets, and page 262 of your textbook. If we're following the US law and say</p>
  <p><em>if one is consuming an alcoholic beverage then one is at least age 21</em></p>
  <p>then you would agree that</p>
  <p><em>if one is under the age of 21 then one is not consuming an alcoholic beverage.</em></p>
  <p>If we label the first statement as <m>P\implies Q</m>, then the second statement is <m>\sim Q\implies \sim P</m>.</p>
  <p>In <term>``proof by contrapositive"</term> we will use that a statement and its contrapositive are logically equivalent to our advantage. Instead of proving the original statement, we do a direct proof of the contrapositive. Note that proof by contrapositive is really just another type of direct proof.</p>
  <p><term>Example:</term> Suppose we want to do proof by contrapositive of the statement</p>
  <p><em>For all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, if <m>n^2</m> is odd, then <m>n</m> is odd.</em></p>
  <p>Then instead we would prove</p>
  <p><em>For all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, if <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^2</m> is odd.</em></p>
  <p>Notice that</p>
  <ul>
    <li><p>Taking the contrapositive of the conditional statement does not affect the quantifier at the start. We still need to prove this statement for all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>.</p></li>
    <li><p>When we negate ``<m>n</m> is odd'' we get ``<m>n</m> is not odd", but every non-odd integer is even, so instead we write ``<m>n</m> is even.</p></li>
  </ul>
  <p><term>Proof Writing:</term> Here's a proof by contrapositive of the statement in the example. Underline the parts that would be included in all proofs by contrapositive.</p>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>For all <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>, if <m>n^2</m> is odd, then <m>n</m> is odd.</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <proof>
    <p>We will prove this using the contrapositive, which is: For all <m>n\in \mathbb{N}</m>, iff <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^{2}</m> is even. So, let <m>n\in\mathbb{N}</m>. We begin by assuming that <m>n</m> is even. By definition of even there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that <m>n = 2m</m>. Substituting, we have 
	\begin{align}
		n^{2} = (2m)^{2} = 4m^{2} = 2(2m^{2}).
	\end{align}
	We know that <m>m</m> and <m>2</m> are integers, and the integers are closed under and multiplication. Thus <m>p = 2m^{2}+2m</m> is also an integer. Thus equation (\ref{eqn:n^2}) shows that <m>n^{2}</m> can be written in the form <m>2p</m> where <m>p</m> is an integer. By definition of even, this shows that <m>n^{2}</m> is even. This completes the proof of the contrapositive, showing that if <m>n^{2}</m> is odd, then <m>n</m> is odd.</p>
  </proof>
  <activity>
    <introduction>
      <p>For each of the following statements, find the contrapositive (turning the statement into an ``if-then" conditional statement if needed). Then decide which one seems easier to prove - the statement or its contrapositive, and briefly explain why.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>For all natural numbers <m>n</m>, if <m>3\nmid n</m> then <m>9\nmid n</m>.</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>For all integers <m>n</m> and <m>m</m>, if <m>nm</m> is even, then <m>n</m> is even or <m>m</m> is even.</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>a,b\in\mathbb{Z}</m>, and let <m>p</m> be a prime. If <m>p\nmid ab</m> then <m>p\nmid a</m> and <m>p\nmid b</m>.</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>For all integers <m>n</m>, if <m>n^2</m> is even if and only if <m>n</m> is even. (Note there are 2 conditional statements here, write out both conditional statements and their contrapositives.)</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>For all integers <m>n</m>, if <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^2-4n+7</m> is even.</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>For all <m>n\in\mathbb{Z}</m>, if <m>n^2-4n+7</m> is even, then <m>n</m> is odd.</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>No prime number greater than <m>3</m> is followed by a perfect square. (Rewrite as a conditional statement first!)</p>
        <p>{\tiny  Easier to prove the original  Easier to prove the contrapositive }</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <activity workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Prove the following <term>biconditional</term> theorem. This means you need to prove 2 conditional statements!</p>
    </statement>
  </activity>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>For all integers <m>n</m>, <m>n^2-4n+7</m> is odd if and only if <m>n</m> is event.</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <activity workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Prove the following <term>biconditional</term> theorem. This means you need to prove 2 conditional statements!</p>
    </statement>
  </activity>
  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>For all integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, <m>3\mid mn</m>  if and only if <m>3\mid m</m> or <m>3\mid n</m>.</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
